obo:GO_0098971  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_5227  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 1, 2: reverse-IP in rat brain showed SEPT9 (SEPTIN9) interacts with KIF17.\n\nFigure 2, 3: fluorescence microscopy images of a rat hippocampal neuron showed these proteins partially colocalize.\n\nFigure 4: SEPT9 interferes with the binding of mLin-10 (aka. Mint1, gene APBA1) to the C-terminal tail of KIF17.\n\nFigure 5: SEPT9 down-regulates the transport of NR2B cargo without interfering with the motility of KIF17.\n\nAuthors summarized:\n\"The inhibition of KIF17-mLin10 binding by SEPT9, which interacts preferentially with the cargo-binding conformation of KIF17, and the partial colocalization of SEPT9 with KIF17 suggest that SEPT9 triggers the release of cargo by binding KIF17 selectively and/or transiently. Thus SEPT9 may provide a new mechanism for the unloading of KIF17 cargo under the control of spatial and temporal cues. Given that septins localize to dendritic branch points and at the base of protrusive structures, including dendritic spines, axonal filopodia, and primary cilia (Tada et al., 2007; Xie et al., 2007; Hu et al., 2010, 2012), septins could mediate the release of cargo at these intracellular sites and compartments.\". Experimental description: Only rats have been used, but the species of the overexpressed mCherry and GFP constructs is not described.\n\nantibody:\nrabbit anti-SEPT9 (Proteintech)" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2023-03-04" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5227" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

